{"id":"quant-ph/0206024","submitter":"Michael Fleischhauer","authors":"Claudia Mewes and Michael Fleischhauer","title":"Two-photon linewidth of light \"stopping\" via electromagnetically induced\n  transparency","comments":"2 figures","journal-ref":null,"doi":"10.1103/PhysRevA.66.033820","report-no":null,"categories":"quant-ph","license":null,"abstract":"  We analyze the two-photon linewidth of the recently proposed adiabatic\ntransfer technique for ``stopping'' of light using electromagnetically induced\ntransparency (EIT). We shown that a successful and reliable transfer of\nexcitation from light to atoms and back can be achieved if the spectrum of the\ninput probe pulse lies within the initial transparency window of EIT, and if\nthe two-photon detuning $\\delta$ is less than the collective coupling strength\n(collective vacuum Rabi-frequency) $g\\sqrt{N}$ divided by $\\sqrt{\\gamma T}$,\nwith $\\gamma$ being the radiative decay rate, $N$ the effective number of atoms\nin the sample, and $T$ the pulse duration. Hence in an optically thick medium\nlight ``storage'' and retrieval is possible with high fidelity even for systems\nwith rather large two-photon detuning or inhomogeneous broadening.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Tue, 4 Jun 2002 19:17:12 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Tue, 4 Jun 2002 21:30:41 GMT"}],"update_date":"2009-11-07"}
